.IX Title "FIND-COMPOUNDS 1"
.TH FIND-COMPOUNDS 1 "2011-04-01" "perl v5.8.8" "User Contributed Perl Documentation"
.SH "NAME"
find\-compounds.pl \- find compound words in a text that are specified in a list.
.SH "DESCRIPTION"
.IX Header "DESCRIPTION"
See perldoc find\-compounds.pl 
.SH "USAGE"
.IX Header "USAGE"
find\-compounds.pl SourceFile CompoundWordList 
.SH "INPUT"
.IX Header "INPUT"
.Sh "Required Arguments:"
.IX Subsection "Required Arguments:"
SourceFile
.IX Subsection "SourceFile"
.PP
Source file is the original text file.
.PP
CompoundWordList
.IX Subsection "CompoundWordList"
.PP
Compound word list contains the compound words. Compound words
are seperated by underscore \*(L"_\*(R". Each compound word is a line. 
.PP
\fIExamples:\fR
.IX Subsection "Examples:"
.PP
The original text contains \*(L"This is the new york city\*(R". In the 
compound word list, it has
.PP
.Vb 2
\& new_york
\& new_york_city
.Ve
.PP
The find\-compounds.pl will find the longest match. After replace
the compound words, the text is \*(L"This is the new_york_city\*(R". 
.PP
\fIOther Options:\fR
.IX Subsection "Other Options:"
.PP
\-\-newline
.IX Subsection "--newline"
.PP
Find compound words within one line boundary with this option. If run
find\-compounds.pl without this option, find compound words crossing
lines. 
